1 . Purpose of this project and description of the data¶

We want, with the features we could collected concerning a project to determine his duration. We have several features, some numerical, some categorial.

At first, we will focus on the numerical and Boolean values to check if a pattern could be show off. As we used already done event, we could calculate his duration as a predictive value. For this first part of this project, we will use mainly linear regression to predict the duration.

In the second part, we will use hierarchical classification tree to start to have check the categorial feature and improve our prediction.

As it is a real project, data are confidential and will be anonymize and features name will be renamed to avoid guessing the real values of this data.

This project, as describe later, will focus only on full completed data.

1.2 Data Description¶

As already explained, data could be described in detail but only type of data. Data coming from our organization. Unfortunately, all features weren’t be completed and we face to missing values. Some features could be used as more than 50 % of values is missing. Also, we could these features in a second part of the project, with classification and by clusters of the data.

We have more than 395 events, but only 93 are fully completed, with 28 features. Data came from a database, and the file is a tabulated csv file.

First, we have 6 features describe the event, it is descriptive and categorical features.

Second, 7 features are duration, 12 are numerical and 3 are Boolean.

The output feature is, also a duration.

4. Linear Regression¶

4.1 Linear Regression¶

We will perform a Multiple Linear Regression with the feature there are not correlation.

First, we will create function

In [44]:
def find_best(df, output = None, liste = None, printed = False):
    best = ['',0]
    
    if liste is None:
        liste = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()
        liste = liste[:-1]
    
    if output is None:
        output = df.columns[-1]

    for p in liste:
        x = df[p]
        y = df[output]
        
        X = np.column_stack((x, np.ones(x.shape[0])))
        model  = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
        
        if printed:
            print(p, model.rsquared)
        if model.rsquared>best[1]:
            best = [p, model.rsquared]
    
    if printed:
        print()
        print('------------------- Best Feature ----------------------')
        print(best[0] + ' : ' + str(best[1]))
        print('-------------------------------------------------------')
        print()
    
    return best
In [45]:
def init_predict_multi(X_train, X_test, output):
    adjr2 = [[], [], [], []]
    
    y = X_train[output]
    y_test = X_test[output]
    x_test = np.ones(X_test.shape[0])
    
    return (x_test, y_test, y, adjr2)
In [46]:
def predict_multi(X_train, X_test, y, x_test, y_test, best, adjr2, X = None, printed = False):
    x = X_train[best]
    
    if X is None:
        X = np.column_stack((X_train[best], np.ones(x.shape[0])))
    else:
        X = np.column_stack((X, X_train[best]))
        
    train = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    
    if printed:
        print(train.summary())
        
    x_test = np.column_stack((x_test, X_test[best]))
    yhat = train.predict(x_test)
    yhat_train = train.predict(X)
    
    rmse_test = np.sqrt(np.mean((yhat - y_test)**2))
    rmse_train = np.sqrt(np.mean((yhat_train - y_train)**2))
        
    adjr2[0].append(train.rsquared)
    adjr2[1].append(train.rsquared_adj)
    adjr2[2].append(rmse_test)
    adjr2[3].append(rmse_train)
    
    return X, x_test, adjr2
In [47]:
def predict_multi_all_features(df):
    best_liste = []
    
    liste = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()
    liste = liste[:-1]
    liste_loop = liste.copy()
    X = None

    # Initialisation des paramètres
    x_test, y_test, y, adjr2 = init_predict_multi(X_train, X_test, 
                                                  df_dropped.columns[-1])

    for p in liste_loop:
        best = find_best(X_train, liste = liste)
        best_liste.append(best)

        # Prediction
        X, x_test, adjr2 = predict_multi(X_train, X_test, y, x_test, y_test, 
                                         best[0], adjr2, X)

        # Remove best from the liste
        liste.remove(best[0])
        
    return adjr2, best_liste
In [48]:
def moyenne(liste, multi = False):
    num_rows = len(liste)
    num_cols = len(liste[0])

    totals = num_cols * [0.0]

    for line in liste:
        for index in range(num_cols):
            if multi == False:
                totals[index] += line[index]
            else:
                totals[index] += line[index][multi]

    return [total / num_rows for total in totals]
In [49]:
r2 = []
adjr2 = []
rsme_test = []
rsme_train = []

for _ in range(10):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_dropped, df_dropped['Output'], test_size=0.2)
    result, best = predict_multi_all_features(X_train)
    r2.append(result[0])
    adjr2.append(result[1])
    rsme_test.append(result[2])
    rsme_train.append(result[3])

r2_mean = moyenne(r2)
adjr2_mean = moyenne(adjr2)
rsme_test_mean = moyenne(rsme_test)
rsme_train_mean = moyenne(rsme_train)
In [51]:
r2 = []
adjr2 = []
rsme_test = []
rsme_train = []
best_liste = []

for _ in range(100):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_dropped, df_dropped['Output'], test_size=0.2)
    result, best = predict_multi_all_features(X_train)
    r2.append(result[0])
    adjr2.append(result[1])
    rsme_test.append(result[2])
    rsme_train.append(result[3])
    best = sorted(best)
    best_liste.append(best)

r2_mean = moyenne(r2)
adjr2_mean = moyenne(adjr2)
rsme_test_mean = moyenne(rsme_test)
rsme_train_mean = moyenne(rsme_train)
best_mean = moyenne(best_liste, 1)

best_feature_sorted = sorted(best_feature_dictionary, 
                             key=best_feature_dictionary.get, reverse=True)

r2 = []
adjr2 = []
rsme_test = []
rsme_train = []
best_liste = []

for _ in range(100):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_dropped[feature_w_o_correlated], df_dropped['Output'], test_size=0.2)
    result, best = predict_multi_all_features(X_train)
    r2.append(result[0])
    adjr2.append(result[1])
    rsme_test.append(result[2])
    rsme_train.append(result[3])
    best = sorted(best)
    best_liste.append(best)

r2_mean = moyenne(r2)
adjr2_mean = moyenne(adjr2)
rsme_test_mean = moyenne(rsme_test)
rsme_train_mean = moyenne(rsme_train)
best_mean = moyenne(best_liste, 1)

Conclusion¶

We didin't have enough information to be able to predict the duration of the event with the data we collect. Further investigation, and more features collection could lead to a better prediction.

We have to go deeper in the EDA, first by splitting by categories to see if there are some underlying pattern.
